  "text": "Preliminary experiments demonstrated that pSB2 was typically heat-inducible in transfected somatic cells (not shown). The pattern of pSB2 heat-inducibility was studied in growing mouse oocytes by injecting 500 to 2000 copies of ScaI-linearized plasmid/GV (Fig. 3A) . Injected oocytes were incubated at 37°C for increasing times, heat-shocked at 43°C for 30 min, recovered at 37°C for 3 h to allow construct expression [CITATION_1] , and then individually processed for biochemical ␤-galactosidase assay. Control oocytes were treated as described above, but were constantly maintained at 37°C. pSB2 heat-inducibility appeared as soon as 6 h postinjection (p.i.) and maximized at 10 h p.i. irrespectively of the number of construct copies injected. Levels of reporter enzyme activity were propor- tional to the number of input plasmid copies. Additional cytochemical ␤-galactosidase assays also showed that pSB2 was heat-activated with a similar kinetics in virtually all manipulated oocytes (Fig. 3B ). The detailed relationship between the number of pSB2 copies injected and the amount of ␤-galactosidase synthesized after heat shock was then determined by heat-shocking pSB2-injected oocytes at 17 h p.i. The dose-response curve obtained in these experiments ( Fig. 3C ) made it possible to consistently determine the absolute number of functional pSB2 molecules that a single oocyte carried at the time of heat shock by the level of the ␤-galactosidase activity produced, in the range of 100 to 2000 pSB2 molecules.",
